ple’s complex relationship with the diversity and multiculturalism that has grown and developed around them. Aging in a Changing World takes a look at how some older people in New Zealand have been responding to and interacting with the new multiculturalism they now encounter in their daily lives. Through their unhurried, micro, daily interactions with immigrants, they quietly emerge as agents of the very social change they are assumed to oppose.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMulticulturalismzNew ZealandxPublic opinion. 0aOlder peoplezNew ZealandxAttitudes. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAging, age studies, sociology, anthropology, New Zealand, New Zealanders, multiculturalism, culture, immigration, immigrants, migration, Brexit, Brexit vote, 2016 election, Donald Trump, stereotypes, racism, racist, nostalgia, nostalgic, diversity, social change, global movement, urbanism, change, mentoring, family, old, young, elderly, elderly care, elderly perspective, medicine, health, political change, economic change.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076647940uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9781978809444?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978809444423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978809444/original  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075418-6  EBO